## Files

```
ai-chat-assistant/
├── index.html   — the app layout and structure
├── style.css    — all the styling, dark theme, animations
├── script.js    — API calls, message handling, chat history
└── README.md    — you're reading it
```

---

## How to run it yourself

### Step 1 — Get a Groq API key

Go to [console.groq.com](https://console.groq.com), sign up for free (no card required), then go to API Keys and create one. Your key will start with `gsk_`.

### Step 2 — Add the key to the project

Open `script.js` and on line 9, replace the placeholder with your actual key:

```javascript
const API_KEY = 'gsk_your_key_goes_here';
```

### Step 3 — Run it

You can't just double-click `index.html` because the browser will block the API call. Instead, run a quick local server:

```bash
cd ai-chat-assistant
python -m http.server 8000
```

Then open `http://localhost:8000` in your browser. That's it.

If you use VS Code, the Live Server extension works too — just right-click `index.html` and hit Open with Live Server.

---

## Hosting it for free

I deployed this on GitHub Pages which is completely free. Steps:

1. Create a repo on GitHub called `ai-chat-assistant`
2. Upload the three files — `index.html`, `style.css`, `script.js`
3. Go to Settings → Pages → set source to main branch → save
4. Wait about a minute and it'll be live

One thing worth knowing — your API key will be visible in the source code since this runs entirely in the browser. That's fine for a portfolio project, but if you ever build something for real users you'd want a backend to keep the key hidden.

---

## Groq free tier

Groq's free tier is genuinely generous. Here's what you get:

| | |
|--|--|
| Requests per day | 14,400 |
| Requests per minute | 30 |
| Tokens per minute | 6,000 |
| Cost | Free |

Way more than enough for personal use or a portfolio demo.

---

## Changing things

**Want to use a different model?** Change line 11 in `script.js`:
```javascript
const MODEL = 'llama-3.3-70b-versatile';   // what I used
const MODEL = 'mixtral-8x7b-32768';         // another free option on Groq
```

**Want to change how the AI behaves?** Edit the `SYSTEM_PROMPT` at the top of `script.js`. That's the instruction it follows before every conversation.

**Want different starter prompts?** Find the suggest-btn buttons in `index.html` and change the text inside them.

---

## What I got out of building this

Before this I hadn't worked directly with AI APIs, so this was a good learning experience. A few things I picked up:

- How to make API calls using the Fetch API with async/await
- How to structure a multi-turn conversation (sending message history with each request so the AI has context)
- How to persist state across sessions using localStorage
- Writing a basic markdown parser in JavaScript to format AI responses nicely
- Building a layout that works properly on both desktop and mobile

